Triumph of the right-wing populists in Austria, they have 29 percent of the total
According to preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria have led to a significant weakening of the two parties in the current grand coalition, as well as a marked strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), whose position as the current chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously threatened, is suffering particularly heavy losses.
The electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the national political scene.
According to the preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain the country's leading political force with 29.8 percent of the vote, but compared to the 2006 elections they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent lost almost nine percent of the vote, ended up even worse.
This is the worst result of the two major parties in the post-war period, and for the People's Party, which triggered the snap elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Even in early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
And yet, the voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations were voiced about the possible resignation of the party leader and current Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary council of the party leadership.
Such a development would, a priori, facilitate the path to the outcome of the election which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the FPÖ would have won 18 percent of the vote and the BZÖ 11 percent - the socialists at the same time expressed fears of a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still united, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ split) on a joint government, which even triggered sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already said that he is ready to work with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently relying on this development.
The last party to gain access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell back from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four per cent threshold and entered parliament.
