If the problem of Czech researchers accused of illegally collecting cockroaches in India were not resolved, the result would be, according to the Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg, a certain cooling of relations between the two countries.
The minister said this today in New York after meeting with his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem was not solved, then yes, some cooling would occur", he said after the meeting, which was organised on the initiative of the Czech Republic.
Mukherjee said, coming out of the talks, that the executive branch could hardly intervene in judicial matters.
He mentioned, however, that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was acquitted and fined, the central government could negotiate with the local government, the Darjeling, as the case was under the jurisdiction of the Darjeling.
"His problem could be solved", said the minister.
Mukherjee said the best solution for Emil Kučera, who was sentenced to three years in prison, would be to appeal to a higher court.
He could then ask for bail and await trial in freedom, he explained.
Schwarzenberg confirmed that his partner had expressed the same view during the talks.
"He advises that he should appeal to a higher court, after which he could be pardoned", said the head of Czech diplomacy.
The only way the Czech side can intervene in this case is to provide the convicts with "competent legal support", the Indian minister said.
He also said that such aid had already been provided by India.
"We want above all to keep the best relations with India, which have a tradition going back many years.
