Czech referee for the sea-bottom fight
He approaches an electronic map on the wall, depicting Australia and its adjacent marine areas.
But he's not interested in the continent. He's interested in a little spot in the blue ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area is as large as the continent itself", says Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea's 30-member team.
Its head, the director of the division, Czech jurist Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
The atmosphere is one of zeal and enthusiasm.
The seabed is a little-known world, rich in natural resources.
There may be oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also living organisms as yet unknown, which may contain the key to the development of a drug against cancer.
A deeper world than the dry land
The coastal states have recently begun to aspire with vengeance to new underwater territories.
They are exercising their rights, as agreed upon in a 1982 UN convention at Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is especially the area of what is called the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometres from the coast of the country concerned.
The latter can, according to the convention, claim exclusively all resources of the continental shelf.
"For simplicity, the continental shelf is the part of the seabed and its subsoil that forms a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles which represent the exclusive economic zone", explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the outer boundaries of the continental shelf must be supported by a large scientific and technical documentation, based on many costly surveys and measurements.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the committee with legal and scientific-technical support.
So far, the committee has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
Only the last three countries have been successful so far", adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, the first country to significantly expand its submarine fleet, has recently been a global phenomenon.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the area of the seabed, which the commission awarded it last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometres, which is six times the size of the country.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The future benefits they will derive from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they project, be inestimable.
Gradually, other countries will also submit their own applications.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
Here, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, declared by convention "the common heritage of mankind".
No State can now have an exclusive position.
The right to extract in this area is allocated by an international institution established by convention.
"But make no mistake, the seabed is not a Klondike", says Director Mikulka, adding that "they are clearly defined and their regime is enshrined in a contract".
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed is now also part of the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern bloc in the framework of the joint organization Interoceanmetal.
In 1991, the Community, together with investors from a number of other States, was granted the status of a so-called 'pioneer investor' under the Convention.
It has the right to extract in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area the investor is prospecting for is slightly larger than the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is moving, it's a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract from a total area of 75,000 square kilometres.
The area is rich in polymetallic deposits containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese", said Ind Pakshi Rajan, another legal expert.
