Turkey is broadening its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey was considering joining the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate its hinterland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 paces from Asia, lies one of the finest relics of his fallen imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed in a neo-renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guides tell us.
The monument is arranged on horseback at the bottom of the platforms, equipped with an observation tower at each of its corners, like some German provincial town halls.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, we have no doubt as to the greatness of the enterprise, which represents a passage to the west.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German association, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, lagging behind the imperialist game, wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination through this railway that reached Damascus, Baghdad and the land better known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, brought about by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is over.
The British and Imperial forces advanced beyond Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded, destroying its roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been slowly falling into ruin, engulfed in the tangles of history.
But today, the railway to Anatolia and all the eastern points, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expansion of Turkey's diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, engendered by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has led to a
Now it is time for a new engagement policy.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded a sleeping car to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit Suat Kiniklioglu, a Turkish AKP MP and one of the foreign policy experts.
The next morning, after a ten-and-a-half hour journey, shaken by noisy tracks whose cadence reminded me of the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived in the Turkish capital - presented as a new city of a new secular state, turning its back on its German past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots, represents an example of the change of the Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, and especially Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a state-of-the-art structure, built of stone and steel, in a developing area, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and many pastry shops where middle managers in suits and ties - men and women - meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
He's got a suit and a tie and even a Blackberry.
"the aim of this foreign policy is to now reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its home country.
Now she has to look east and west at the same time.
It was not the case with either.
She had to do both.
But at a certain point, I asked if Turkey should not choose.
"Turkey", he said, "does not want to have to choose between the two".
He then pointed out something that almost everyone I spoke to had recited to me: The Turkish railway does not only go to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, so it is as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as for Turkey itself.
With the integration of Turkey, the message seems to be that Europe is metaphorically travelling on rails to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpasha station, after another night's sleeplessness, I thought of these two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had followed the construction of this building 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that the European ambitions of the Middle East could, in large part, be in the hands of Turkey.
As I waited at the terminal for the ferry to cross the Bosphorus, I remembered the time when Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
At least there's no longer any doubt on the continent that this country could claim to be fascinating.
