The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It's called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, and it represents the first steps towards collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at the Advanced Technology Center of Nissan Motor Co. have built this small robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Center of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the general director of public relations for the Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan Safety Shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan Safety Shield.
But most important of all are the bee's compound eyes, which can see in more than 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles within a two-meter radius and within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance to that object, and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"When it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by forking its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Motion Laboratory and the project's chief engineer.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it to do, not in infinite directions like bees.
For this purpose, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
"Every second this device has to just process information and act on that data.
It doesn't need to retain the information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
This may surprise you, but we are not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes".
This represents the first development of new instant collision avoidance technology, a technology that will be introduced in mass-produced cars in about ten years from now, according to Nissan.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future application of this technology could be to adapt this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
