Morgan Stanley opens up its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced that Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan's largest bank, will buy 21% of its shares for $9 billion, a move that has been accompanied by a sharp fall in its stock market.
A week after unveiling a provisional agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common stock at a price of $25.25 per share, for a total amount of $3 billion.
The price used is 19% below the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in convertible securities, which will provide it with a 10% return and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be executed at an average unit price of $29 per share, 28% above its current price.
Morgan Stanley shares, however, were down 6.79% to $23.07 at about 17:00 GMT.
"This strategic alliance is a significant opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to banking holding status", said John Mack, the US group's chief executive.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its business but places it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday further show that the deal has been modified in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago", explained Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, in Tokyo, "we thought that the participation would be entirely in ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimise the risks and cover ourselves".
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley shares 7% below their book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of approximately 20% of earnings per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG may convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares within one year if the latter trade more than 50% above the conversion price, or about $47, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital provided by MUFG will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group, however, declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG's investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of approximately 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "dramatically" reduced its balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been difficult for the group, which has seen its stock price melt in half as the cost of insurance against default on its debt skyrocketed.
This cost was recovering on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
