Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
To rebuild the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, the Bolivian Evo Morales and the Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he was the third to vote on a draft of a new Constitution.
The mission was accomplished, as 64% of the electorate voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results showing 80% of the votes cast.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, he needed half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and a count by a non-governmental organization had predicted a large victory for the "yes" side, with a margin of victory of 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution has triumphed in an overwhelming way", he said, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was held in a calm manner according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving for it the "planning of development" of a country that lives mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currency sent by its emigrants.
The bill, which was introduced by Correa, elected in 2006, also grants stronger powers to the head of state, who can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and has the ability to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president has begun to implement in this country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando has launched an assault against the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who were held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
The hostages, apparently in good shape, arrived at about 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at the al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, by helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in 'good health', and 'no ransom has been paid' to the kidnappers", said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
The group of hostages were taken on a four-wheel drive safari on September 19 at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the border of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and were tossed from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It comprises 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous agency, which organizes the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces, flown in two helicopters, launched the attack in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of fire took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled", said the official, who requested anonymity.
He said that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces unit "Blitz" had been sent to Sudan in total, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister, Franco Frattini, spoke from Belgrade, where he is based, of the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We must acknowledge that we achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men in the intelligence services, special forces", he said, without giving further details.
He also denied that a ransom was paid.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on patrol carrying the kidnappers, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The military claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), which was immediately denied by the movement.
