Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries are helping the Belgo-Dutch bank, the first European banking institution to be in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourgish and Dutch governments reached agreement at the highest level on this matter, also calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been widening for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy up almost half (49%) of the bank's capital in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell some of its holdings, including, in the first place, the mainly insurance business acquired last year from the Dutch company ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares started to plummet. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is far too large to be allowed to fail.
On Friday alone, the company's stock fell 12 percent, to its lowest level in 14 years.
Since January, the stock has lost more than two-thirds of its value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's managers, is not realistic.
The company's management blames the uncertainty overseas, in connection with the adoption of the US rescue plan of 700 billion dollars, for the fall in Fortis shares.
The papers have already received a slight increase on Monday.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed to head the bank, as the new managing director.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but had not yet received a substantive proposal.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors need not worry, they will not lose their money.
There was no panic among the bank's clientele and no agencies were stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate based on information about his drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of information on prescribing medicines, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting your chicken coop to a fox", Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions for medicines, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage dependent on the state of health of the client who comes, and if they think the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination and only signed insurance contracts with them after they had heard the results.
For the last ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies the data concerning the purchase of medicines by the person in the last eighteen months.
For example, if a person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, placing him immediately in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of this program in circulation, some of which determine a risk factor at the same time, so there is little left for the insurer to do other than the paperwork, but tiny problems can still arise.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that one drug can be used for different purposes, for example, some mixtures can be used for migraines or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in research and data analysis, and they have to ask permission from the patient before they can collect the necessary information from the pharmacy.
Now they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their misconduct in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to data on the use of medication, thus providing an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time it is becoming increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to extend the scope of government control over companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard recognises that this is not enough and that is why he has developed his programme even further, which would make the transmission of data conditional on the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurers do not sign an insurance contract with him.
So, in the end, the chickens are dependent on the fox's kindness.
The overall menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners to each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other issues, which are largely global.
Today there will also be a France-India summit, where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be the main topic.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given a wider say in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi's candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too long on this issue yesterday at the 9th summit held in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, the current President of the Union, Commission President Barroso and the head of the diplomatic service, Javier Solana, met the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double their trade in five years, an increase of more than 100 billion euros.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007, the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious target.
In this sense, they have harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil aviation from a legal point of view, which will allow air traffic to grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009 at the latest.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's largest trading partner, on one side, and New Delhi, the EU's ninth largest trading partner, on the other.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as were all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a UN conference on the subject was mentioned.
The completion of the Doha round of trade deals has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed its commitment to its energy and climate agenda, including a target to reduce its toxic emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the fact that a global market should be established at the climate conference next year, and that greenhouse gas emissions should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wanted to prevent the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is today visiting the French capital, where he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the information of the press agency, the agreement would last for 15 years.
In Frankfurt, more than three hundred Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers attended the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international event in the exchange of rights.
The International Book Fair in Frankfurt is expecting more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 different countries to occupy the 171,790 square meters of the fair with more than 403,000 titles on display, with Turkey as the guest of honor.
The Italian Government will be represented by the Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities, Francesco Maria Giro, at the opening ceremony of the Italian Papillon: Italy will be present in an institutional way, with an Italy Point - 264 square metres of exhibition space.
It will be followed by a meeting with the press in the Structure Room, in Hall 5.0 of the Buchmesse: an opportunity to present figures, trends and prospects on the position of publishing in Italy.
According to the data, the importance of books by foreign authors is gradually decreasing in relation to the total Italian production, and in particular in relation to that for adults and children.
We found the plane belonging to Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the desert of Nevada, has been found.
The debris was found on a 3,000-meter-high plateau in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, there are no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one that Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared", he said at a press conference.
So the sheriff made it clear that no human remains were found on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead.
The US Transportation Safety Bureau (NTSB) said that a few hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it is indeed the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal effects were found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
It's two documents bearing Fosset's name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was stopped a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had earned a place in history by setting a long series of records.
On his sixth attempt, in 2002, he became the first man to complete a round the world flight in a hot air balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world non-stop.
Among these records was the one of flying to 15,445 meters in the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
